lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Lawmakers in the House are using the public impeachment hearings to highlight their respective views of President Trump’s unusual foreign policy with Ukraine. But two Intelligence Committee lawyers are asking many of the questions.

abstract: In the second week of impeachment hearings, White House national security aides recalled their concerns after the president’s conversation with his Ukrainian counterpart.
snippet: In the second week of impeachment hearings, White House national security aides recalled their concerns after the president’s conversation with his Ukrainian counterpart.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Two White House national security officials testified before the House’s impeachment inquiry on Tuesday that President Trump’s request to Ukraine’s president to investigate Democratic rivals was inappropriate, and one of them said it validated his “worst fear” that American policy toward that country would veer off course.

headline_main: Trade deal, Impeachment Hearings, Bei Bei: Your Wednesday Briefing

abstract: The first of the “three amigos” will testify before the House Intelligence Committee on Tuesday afternoon.
snippet: The first of the “three amigos” will testify before the House Intelligence Committee on Tuesday afternoon.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — As the impeachment inquiry has picked up speed in recent weeks, Americans have heard a lot about the “three amigos” — a trio of Washington figures who worked with President Trump’s personal lawyer, Rudolph W. Giuliani, to carry out Mr. Trump’s plan for Ukraine to investigate his political rivals.

abstract: Joseph R. Biden Jr. has durable support from a multiracial coalition of working-class voters who view him as one of their own.
snippet: Joseph R. Biden Jr. has durable support from a multiracial coalition of working-class voters who view him as one of their own.
lead_paragraph: WEST POINT, Iowa — They are white and nonwhite alike, prefer Facebook over Twitter, if they are on social media at all, and can be hard to find at Democratic campaign events dominated by activists from the professional class. But these blue-collar voters could go a long way toward determining who captures the Democratic presidential nomination — and Joseph R. Biden Jr. is racing to press his advantage with that constituency.
